SIMPLE: stimulate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stimulate
<hw>Stim"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Stimulated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Stimulating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>stimulatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>stimulare</ets> to prick or goad
on, to incite, fr. <ets>stimulus</ets> a goad. See
<er>Stimulus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To excite as if with a goad;
to excite, rouse, or animate, to action or more vigorous exertion by
some pungent motive or by persuasion; <as>as, to <ex>stimulate</ex> one
by the hope of reward, or by the prospect of glory</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To excite and <qex>stimulate</qex> us thereunto.</q> <rj><qau>Dr.
J. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>To excite; to irritate;
especially, to excite the activity of (a nerve or an irritable muscle),
as by electricity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To animate; incite; encourage; impel; urge;
instigate; irritate; exasperate; incense.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stimulation</ent>⟦br⟧
